Extend rules to support @Rule public MethodRule someRule() { return new SomeRule(); }

The problem is that Scala does not allow the creation of public fields. If you
declare a field public, the field is created as private but with accessor
methods.
To allow the use of @Rule with Scala methods, this patch allows the addition
of @Rule to methods. When BlockJUnit4ClassRunner retrieves the list of fields
that have the @Rule annotation, it also searches for methods with @Rule.
These methods are called and the values returned are added to the list of
TestRule.

@ClassRule has been similarly changed.

This is intended to be used as follows:

private ExpectedException foobar = rules.ExpectedException.none();

@Rule public ExpectedException getFoobar() {
    return foobar;
}

The validation is exactly the same as for the fields, i.e the methods must be
public and return a TestRule/MethodRule. In the case of @ClassRule, the
methods must also be static.

There was not way to modify categories outside the s/w layer until now. So for example in practical point of view you need to specify categories via properties and to make a group of categories narrow.

For my own purposes, I extended org.junit.experimental.categories.Categories and overloaded the filter. These changes can be implemented to the framework in more elegant way than creating a new custom runner.

Finally my runner works as expected.

As a result, in the surefire's maven plugin i specify properties (or one of them at least) namely:
org.junit.categories.included
org.junit.categories.excluded

<plugin>
<groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
<artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>
<version>2.6</version>
<configuration>
<systemPropertyVariables>
<org.junit.categories.included>org/IRelationalDB.java</org.junit.categories.included>
<org.junit.categories.excluded>org/IRunWithMySQL.java</org.junit.categories.excluded>
</systemPropertyVariables>
</configuration>
</plugin>

and I use the Categories runner with no restrictions in the code against the custom runner.

As an example, we have a super category org.IAllSystems, and other two sub categories org.IRelationalDB and org.INonrelationalDB, and we have two tests with concrete (non) relational Systems:

class TestDBReqNo1836 {// for relational
@Test @Category(IRunWithMySQL.class) public void mySql() {}
@Test @Category(IRunWithOracle.class) public void oracle() {}
}

class TestDBReqNo1837 {// for non-rel
@org.junit.Test @Category(IRunWithAmazonEC2.class) public void amazonEc2() {}
}

After you run the suite like this

@RunWith(Categories.class)
@IncludeCategory(IAllSystems.class)
@SuiteClasses({TestDBReqNo1836.class, TestDBReqNo1837.class})
public final class DBTestSuite {}

you will get all tests running due to IAllSystems.

Some build processes want to make the super category more narrow using my new properties and the custom runner Categories (same simple name as in junit).
All you have to do is to specify the properties like this:

-Dorg.junit.categories.included=org/categories/IRelationalDB.java
-Dorg.junit.categories.excluded=org/IRunWithMySQL.java

This way you will ignore non-relational systems and filter out the MySql category.

Very easy to use, and no need to modify your code, and no need to make more tailore made suites -only one.

In practice, you have to test several DB users and miscelaneous tables using one connection. Due to e.g. performance reasons you would not reopen a new connection and close the old one.
In worst cases you want to keep the DB connection, and not to lose data with in-memory DB.

In most cases the programmer would share static context among tests through test suite.
Actually dangerous solution!

Here i come with an update to

org.junit.runners.JUnit4
and org.junit.runners.Suite

, where the suite tries to inject suite instance (fail-safe) in to public field on an instance of test annotated by @Parent (must be added to framework).

All loks like this:

```
@RunWith(Suite.class)
@SuiteClasses({MyTest.class})
public final class TestSuite implements IParentDB {
    private final DBConnection connection;

    public TestSuite() {
        connection = new DBConnection();
    }

@Override
    public IDBConnection getConnection() {
        return connection;
    }

@Suite.SuiteFinished
    public void done() {
        if (connection != null) connection.close();
    }

}

@RunWith(org.my.JUnit4.class)
public final class MyTest {

    @Parent
    public IParentDB parent;

    @Test
    public void testDB() {
        assertNotNull(parent);
        assertNotNull(parent.getConnection());
    }
}
```

, where IParentDB  is a custom type.

Thus all the tests similar to MyTest now are able to share DB connection without any need to maintain the test suite vice-versa.

As an advantage, the method done() in the suite is called when all tests finished.

I tested in my scenario with two tests and the single instance of the suite in all the life cycle of both tests.

When integrated to JUNit 4, we would not need to specify a custom @RunWith(org.my.JUnit4.class).

